In this problem we will investigate the United States Gross Domestic Product (GDP). The data file gdp.csv contains the real US GDP, quarterly, from 1946, Q4 to 2014 Q2, seasonally adjusted and inflation adjusted, in billions of 2009 dollars.

Part A

We read the data file and extract the date and gdp columns with the following commands:

library(ggplot2)
data <- read.csv("http://ptrckprry.com/course/forecasting/data/gdp.csv")
date <- as.Date(data$date)
gdp <- data$gdp

Here is a plot of the GDP series versus date:

ggplot() + geom_line(aes(date, gdp)) + ylab("GDP") + xlab(NULL) + labs(title = "US GDP from Q1'46 to Q2'14")

Does GDP seem to grow linearly over time?

The GDP seems to grow (sub)linearly over time as the coefficient value is .5998.

Part B

Here is a plot of log(GDP).

log.gdp <- log(gdp) # create the log(GDP) variable
ggplot() + geom_line(aes(date, log.gdp)) + ylab("Log(GDP)") + xlab(NULL) + labs(title = "Log(US GDP) from Q1'46 to Q2'14")

Does log GDP appear to grow linearly over time? If so, then what does this imply about the growth of GDP itself?

Log GDP grows linearly over time. This approach mitigates for level-dependent volatility which can be seen in the prior graph.

Part C

We fit an ordinary linear regression model for log(GDP), using time as the predictor variable.

log.gdp <- log(gdp)

time <- 1:length(gdp) # create the time variable
model <- lm(log.gdp ~ time)
model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log.gdp ~ time)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         time  
##    7.647331     0.008088

Based on the fitted model, we forecast the log(GDP) for the third quarter of the year 2014 (time = 272).

newdata <- data.frame(time = 272)
predict(model, newdata)
##        1 
## 9.847186

We also construct a 95% prediction interval to go with the point forecast:

predict(model, newdata, interval = 'prediction', level = .95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 9.847186 9.729679 9.964694

Do you think this interval forecast (prediction interval) is valid? Does it seem too wide, or too precise? Explain.

Part D

Next is a plot of the log(GDP) series with the fitted line superimposed.

ggplot() + geom_line(aes(date, log.gdp)) + geom_abline(intercept = 8.400e+00 , slope = 8.857e-05, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') + ylab("Log(GDP)") + xlab(NULL) + labs(title = "Log(US GDP) with Model")

Does the line fit well?

Part E

Here is a plot the residuals from the fitted line versus time.

res <- residuals(model)
ggplot() + geom_point(aes(time, res), colour = 'red') + labs(title = "Residuals Over Time") + ylab("Residuals") + xlab(NULL)

What potential problems with the linear model are indicated by this plot? Do you think these problems could spoil the validity of the forecast interval?
